# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: r-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] A **bounding volume hierarchy** (**BVH**) is a tree structure on a set of geometric objects.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] All geometric objects, which form the leaf nodes of the tree, are wrapped in bounding volumes.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] These nodes are then grouped as small sets and enclosed within larger bounding volumes.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] These, in turn, are also grouped and enclosed within other larger bounding volumes in a recursive fashion, eventually resulting in a tree structure with a single bounding volume at the top of the tree.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Bounding volume hierarchies are used to support several operations on sets of geometric objects efficiently, such as in collision detection and ray tracing.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Although wrapping objects in bounding volumes and performing collision tests on them before testing the object geometry itself simplifies the tests and can result in significant performance improvements, the same number of pairwise tests between bounding volumes are still being performed.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] By arranging the bounding volumes into a bounding volume hierarchy, the time complexity (the number of tests performed) can be reduced to logarithmic in the number of objects.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] With such a hierarchy in place, during collision testing, child volumes do not have to be examined if their parent volumes are not intersected (for example, if the bounding volumes of two bumper cars do not intersect, the bounding volumes of the bumpers themselves need not be checked for collision).
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The choice of bounding volume is determined by a trade-off between two objectives.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] On the one hand, bounding volumes with a very simple shape can be stored in only a few bytes, and intersection tests and distance computations are simple and fast.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] On the other hand, bounding volumes should fit the corresponding data objects very tightly.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] One of the most commonly used bounding volumes is an axis-aligned minimum bounding box.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The axis-aligned minimum bounding box for a given set of data objects is easy to compute, requires only a few bytes to store, and robust intersection tests are easy to implement and extremely fast.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In terms of the structure of BVH, it has to be decided what degree (the number of children) and height to use in the tree representing the BVH.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] A tree of a low degree will be of greater height.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] That increases root-to-leaf traversal time.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] On the other hand, less work has to be expended at each visited node to check its children for overlap.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The opposite holds for a high-degree tree: although the tree will be of smaller height, more work is spent at each node.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In practice, binary trees (degree = 2) are by far the most common.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] One of the main reasons is that binary trees are easier to build.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] There are three primary categories of tree construction methods: top-down, bottom-up, and insertion methods.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The most crucial part for this approach is to decide how to partition objects in a node's region among the node's children.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] This can be done with a splitting plane to split a node's bounding volume into partitions so that having to traverse many child nodes is minimized.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Simply using the midpoint of volume centroids for splitting might be a sub-optimal choice, as illustrated in the figure, where a big overlap volume occurs.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Hence, good splitting criteria such as the surface-area heuristic (SAH) are often used with equal-size buckets of splitting planes, so that only at these splitting points, re-calculation of SAH is required.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] One example for this is the use of a Z-order curve (also known as Morton-order), where clusters can be found by simply taking a linear pass through a Morton-ordered array of leaves.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Given the independent clusters of leaf nodes, sub-trees can be constructed in parallel and then further combined to form higher nodes.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] This parallelization makes the BVH construction very fast and can also be implemented in a hybrid manner, where all sub-trees are combined followed by a top-down approach.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Both top-down and bottom-up methods are considered *off-line methods* as they both require all objects to be available before construction starts.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] *Insertion methods* build the tree by inserting one object at a time, starting from an empty tree.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The insertion location should be chosen that causes the tree to grow as little as possible according to a cost metric.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Insertion methods are considered *on-line methods* since they do not require all objects to be available before construction starts and thus allow updates to be performed at runtime.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] After a BVH tree is constructed, it can then be converted to a compacted form for efficient traversal to improve overall system performance.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The compact representation is often a linear array in memory, where the nodes of the BVH tree are stored in depth-first order.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Hence, for a binary BVH tree, the first child of an internal node will be placed next to itself, and only the offset from the interior node to the index of the second child must be stored explicitly.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The implementation of the traversal can be done without recursive function calls and only a stack is required to store the nodes to be visited next.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The pseudocode provided below is a simple reference for ray tracing applications.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVHs are often used in ray tracing to eliminate potential intersection candidates within a scene by omitting geometric objects located in bounding volumes which are not intersected by the current ray.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] This only requires a small change in line 11-12 of the above pseudo-code.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Similar optimizations during BVH traversal can be employed when descending into child volumes of the second volume, to restrict further search space and thus reduce traversal time.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVHs also naturally support inserting and removing objects without full rebuild, but with resulting BVH having usually worse query performance compared to full rebuild.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVHs can also be combined with scene graph methods, and geometry instancing, to reduce memory usage, improve structure update and full rebuild performance, as well as guide better object or primitive splitting.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVHs are often used for accelerating collision detection computation.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In the context of cloth simulation, BVHs are used to compute collision between a cloth and itself as well as with other objects.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Another powerful use case for BVH is pair-wise distance computation.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] A naive approach to find the minimum distance between two set of objects would compute the distance between all of the pair-wise combinations.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] A BVH allows us to efficiently prune many of the comparisons without needing to compute potentially elaborate distance between the all objects.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVH can significantly accelerate ray tracing applications by reducing the number of ray-surface intersection calculations.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Hardware implementation of BVH operations such as traversal can further accelerate ray-tracing.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Currently, real-time ray tracing is available on multiple platforms.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Hardware implementation of BVH is one of the key innovations making it possible.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In 2018, Nvidia introduced RT Cores with their Turing GPU architecture as part of the RTX platform.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] RT Cores are specialized hardware units designed to accelerate BVH traversal and ray-triangle intersection tests.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The combination of these key features enables real-time ray tracing that can be use for video games. as well as design applications.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] AMD's RDNA (Radeon DNA) architecture, introduced in 2019, has incorporated hardware-accelerated ray tracing since its second iteration, RDNA 2.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The architecture uses dedicated hardware units called Ray Accelerators to perform ray-box and ray-triangle intersection tests, which are crucial for traversing Bounding Volume Hierarchies (BVH).
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In RDNA 2 and 3, the shader is responsible for traversing the BVH, while the Ray Accelerators handle intersection tests for box and triangle nodes.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Originally designed to accelerate ray tracing, researchers are now exploring ways to leverage fast BVH traversal to speed up other applications.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] These include determining the containing tetrahedron for a point, enhancing granular matter simulations, and performing nearest neighbor calculations.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Some methods repurpose Nvidia's RT core components by reframing these tasks as ray-tracing problems.
[src:r-tree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] This direction seems promising as substantial speedups in performance are reported across the various applications.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The performance of R-trees depends on the quality of the algorithm that clusters the data rectangles on a node.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Hilbert R-trees use space-filling curves, and specifically the Hilbert curve, to impose a linear ordering on the data rectangles.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] There are two types of Hilbert R-trees: one for static databases, and one for dynamic databases.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] In both cases Hilbert space-filling curves are used to achieve better ordering of multidimensional objects in the node.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] This ordering has to be "good", in the sense that it should group "similar" data rectangles together, to minimize the area and perimeter of the resulting minimum bounding rectangles (MBRs).
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Packed Hilbert R-trees are suitable for static databases in which updates are very rare or in which there are no updates at all.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The dynamic Hilbert R-tree is suitable for dynamic databases where insertions, deletions, or updates may occur in real time.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Moreover, dynamic Hilbert R-trees employ flexible deferred splitting mechanism to increase the space utilization.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Every node has a well defined set of sibling nodes.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] This is done by proposing an ordering on the R-tree nodes.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The Hilbert R-tree sorts rectangles according to the Hilbert value of the center of the rectangles (i.e., MBR).
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] (The Hilbert value of a point is the length of the Hilbert curve from the origin to the point.) Given the ordering, every node has a well-defined set of sibling nodes; thus, deferred splitting can be used.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] By adjusting the split policy, the Hilbert R-tree can achieve a degree of space utilization as high as desired.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] To the contrary, other R-tree variants have no control over the space utilization.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Although the following example is for a static environment, it explains the intuitive principles for good R-tree design.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] These principles are valid for both static and dynamic databases.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Roussopoulos and Leifker proposed a method for building a packed R-tree that achieves almost 100% space utilization.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The idea is to sort the data on the x or y coordinate of one of the corners of the rectangles.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Sorting on any of the four coordinates gives similar results.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] In this discussion points or rectangles are sorted on the x coordinate of the lower left corner of the rectangle, referred to as a "lowx packed R-tree".
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The sorted list of rectangles is scanned; successive rectangles are assigned to the same R-tree leaf node until that node is full; a new leaf node is then created, and the scanning of the sorted list continues.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Thus, the nodes of the resulting R-tree will be fully packed, with the possible exception of the last node at each level.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Higher levels of the tree are created in a similar way.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Figure 1 highlights the problem of the lowx packed R-tree.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Figure 1 [Right] shows the leaf nodes of the R-tree that the lowx packing method will create for the points of Figure 1 [Left].
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The fact that the resulting father nodes cover little area explains why the lowx packed R-tree achieves excellent performance for point queries.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] However, the fact that the fathers have large perimeters explains the degradation of performance for region queries.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] This is consistent with the analytical formulas for R-tree performance.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Intuitively, the packing algorithm should ideally assign nearby points to the same leaf node.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Ignorance of the y coordinate by the lowx packed R-tree tends to violate this empirical rule.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The section below describes two variants of the Hilbert R-trees.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The first index is suitable for the static database in which updates are very rare or in which there are no updates at all.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The nodes of the resulting R-tree will be fully packed, with the possible exception of the last node at each level.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Thus, the space utilization is ≈100%; this structure is called a packed Hilbert R-tree.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The second index, called a Dynamic Hilbert R-tree, supports insertions and deletions, and is suitable for a dynamic environment.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The following provides a brief introduction to the Hilbert curve.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The basic Hilbert curve on a 2x2 grid, denoted by H1 is shown in Figure 2.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] To derive a curve of order i, each vertex of the basic curve is replaced by the curve of order i – 1, which may be appropriately rotated and/or reflected.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Figure 2 also shows the Hilbert curves of order two and three.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] When the order of the curve tends to infinity, like other space filling curves, the resulting curve is a fractal, with a fractal dimension of two.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The Hilbert curve can be generalized for higher dimensionalities.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Algorithms for drawing the two-dimensional curve of a given order can be found in and.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] An algorithm for higher dimensionalities is given in.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The path of a space filling curve imposes a linear ordering on the grid points; this path may be calculated by starting at one end of the curve and following the path to the other end.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The actual coordinate values of each point can be calculated.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] However, for the Hilbert curve this is much harder than for example the Z-order curve.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Figure 2 shows one such ordering for a 4x4 grid (see curve H2).
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] For example, the point (0,0) on the H2 curve has a Hilbert value of 0, while the point (1,1) has a Hilbert value of 2.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The Hilbert value of a rectangle is defined as the Hilbert value of its center.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The Hilbert curve imposes a linear ordering on the data rectangles and then traverses the sorted list, assigning each set of C rectangles to a node in the R-tree.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The final result is that the set of data rectangles on the same node will be close to each other in the linear ordering, and most likely in the native space; thus, the resulting R-tree nodes will have smaller areas.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Figure 2 illustrates the intuitive reasons why our Hilbert-based methods will result in good performance.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The data is composed of points (the same points as given in Figure 1).
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] By grouping the points according to their Hilbert values, the MBRs of the resulting R-tree nodes tend to be small square-like rectangles.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] This indicates that the nodes will likely have small area and small perimeters.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Small area values result in good performance for point queries; small area and small perimeter values lead to good performance for larger queries.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] (packs rectangles into an R-tree) Step 1.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Calculate the Hilbert value for each data rectangle Step 2.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The assumption here is that the data are static or the frequency of modification is low.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] This is a simple heuristic for constructing an R-tree with ~100% space utilization which at the same time will have a good response time.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The Hilbert R-tree has the following structure.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] A leaf node contains at most Cl entries each of the form (R, obj _id) where Cl is the capacity of the leaf, R is the MBR of the real object (xlow, xhigh, ylow, yhigh) and obj-id is a pointer to the object description record.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The main difference between the Hilbert R-tree and the R*-tree is that non-leaf nodes also contain information about the LHVs (Largest Hilbert Value).
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Notice that since the non-leaf node picks one of the Hilbert values of the children to be the value of its own LHV, there is not extra cost for calculating the Hilbert values of the MBR of non-leaf nodes.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Figure 3 illustrates some rectangles organized in a Hilbert R-tree.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The Hilbert values of the centers are the numbers near the "x" symbols (shown only for the parent node "II").
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Figure 4 shows how the tree of Figure 3 is stored on the disk; the contents of the parent node "II" are shown in more detail.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Every data rectangle in node "I" has a Hilbert value v ≤33; similarly every rectangle in node "II" has a Hilbert value greater than 33 and ≤ 107, etc.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] A plain R-tree splits a node on overflow, creating two nodes from the original one.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] This policy is called a 1-to-2 splitting policy.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] It is possible also to defer the split, waiting until two nodes split into three.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Note that this is similar to the B*-tree split policy.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] This method is referred to as the 2-to-3 splitting policy.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] In general, this can be extended to s-to-(s+1) splitting policy; where s is the order of the splitting policy.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] To implement the order-s splitting policy, the overflowing node tries to push some of its entries to one of its s - 1 siblings; if all of them are full, then s-to-(s+1) split need to be done.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The s -1 siblings are called the cooperating siblings.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Next, the algorithms for searching, insertion, and overflow handling are described in detail.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The searching algorithm is similar to the one used in other R-tree variants.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Starting from the root, it descends the tree and examines all nodes that intersect the query rectangle.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] At the leaf level, it reports all entries that intersect the query window w as qualified data items.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Invoke Search for every entry whose MBR intersects the query window w.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Report all entries that intersect the query window w as candidates.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] To insert a new rectangle r in the Hilbert R-tree, the Hilbert value h of the center of the new rectangle is used as a key.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] At each level the node with the minimum LHV value greater than h of all its siblings is chosen.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] When a leaf node is reached, the rectangle r is inserted in its correct order according to h.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] After a new rectangle is inserted in a leaf node N, **AdjustTree** is called to fix the MBR and largest Hilbert values in the upper-level nodes.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Invoke ChooseLeaf(r, h) to select a leaf node L in which to place r.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] appropriate place according to the Hilbert order and return.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] a new root whose children are the two resulting nodes.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] with the minimum LHV value greater than h.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Set N to the node pointed by ptr and repeat from C2.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] If N has been split, let NN be the new node.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Otherwise, invoke HandleOverflow(Np , NN ).
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Let P be the set of parent nodes for the nodes in S.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Adjust the corresponding MBR's and LHV's of the nodes in P appropriately.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] In the Hilbert R-tree, there is no need to re-insert orphaned nodes whenever a father node underflows.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Instead, keys can be borrowed from the siblings or the underflowing node is merged with its siblings.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] This is possible because the nodes have a clear ordering (according to Largest Hilbert Value, LHV); in contrast, in R-trees there is no such concept concerning sibling nodes.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] Notice that deletion operations require s cooperating siblings, while insertion operations require s - 1 siblings.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] borrow some entries from s cooperating siblings.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] if all the siblings are ready to underflow.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] The overflow handling algorithm in the Hilbert R-tree treats the overflowing nodes either by moving some of the entries to one of the s - 1 cooperating siblings or by splitting s nodes into s +1 nodes.
[src:r-tree/hilbert-r-tree] distribute ε evenly among the s nodes according to Hilbert values.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] A **spatial database** is a general-purpose database (usually a relational database) that has been enhanced to include spatial data that represents objects defined in a geometric space, along with tools for querying and analyzing such data.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] Most spatial databases allow the representation of simple geometric objects such as points, lines and polygons.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] Some spatial databases handle more complex structures such as 3D objects, topological coverages, linear networks, and triangulated irregular networks (TINs).
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] While typical databases have developed to manage various numeric and character types of data, such databases require additional functionality to process spatial data types efficiently, and developers have often added *geometry* or *feature* data types.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] The Open Geospatial Consortium (OGC) developed the *Simple Features* specification (first released in 1997) and sets standards for adding spatial functionality to database systems.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] The *SQL/MM Spatial* ISO/IEC standard is a part of the structured query language and multimedia standard extending the Simple Features.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] The core functionality added by a spatial extension to a database is one or more *spatial datatypes*, which allow for the storage of spatial data as attribute values in a table.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] Most commonly, a single spatial value would be a geometric primitive (point, line, polygon, etc.) based on the vector data model.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] The datatypes in most spatial databases are based on the OGC Simple Features specification for representing geometric primitives.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] Some spatial databases also support the storage of raster data.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] Because all geographic locations must be specified according to a spatial reference system, spatial databases must also allow for the tracking and transformation of coordinate systems.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] In many systems, when a spatial column is defined in a table, it also includes a choice of coordinate system, chosen from a list of available systems that is stored in a lookup table.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] The second major functionality extension in a spatial database is the addition of spatial capabilities to the query language (e.g., SQL); these give the spatial database the same query, analysis, and manipulation operations that are available in traditional GIS software.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] In most relational database management systems, this functionality is implemented as a set of new functions that can be used in SQL SELECT statements.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] Some databases support only simplified or modified sets of these operations, especially in cases of NoSQL systems like MongoDB and CouchDB.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] A **spatial index** is used by a spatial database to optimize spatial queries, implementing spatial access methods.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] Database systems use indices to quickly look up values by sorting data values in a linear (e.g. alphabetical) order; however, this way of indexing data is not optimal for spatial queries in two- or three-dimensional space.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] Instead, spatial databases use a *spatial* index designed specifically for multi-dimensional ordering.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] A **spatial query** is a special type of database query supported by spatial databases, including geodatabases.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] The queries differ from non-spatial SQL queries in several important ways.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] Two of the most important are that they allow for the use of geometry data types such as points, lines and polygons and that these queries consider the spatial relationship between these geometries.
[src:r-tree/point-access-method] The function names for queries differ across geodatabases.
[src:r-tree/priority-r-tree] The **Priority R-tree** is a worst-case asymptotically optimal alternative to the spatial tree R-tree.
[src:r-tree/priority-r-tree] It was first proposed by Arge, De Berg, Haverkort and Yi, K. in an article from 2004.
[src:r-tree/priority-r-tree] The prioritized R-tree is essentially a hybrid between a *k*-dimensional tree and a R-tree in that it defines a given object's N-dimensional bounding volume (called Minimum Bounding Rectangles – MBR) as a point in N-dimensions, represented by the ordered pair of the rectangles.
[src:r-tree/priority-r-tree] The term *prioritized* arrives from the introduction of four priority-leaves that represents the most extreme values of each dimensions, included in every branch of the tree.
[src:r-tree/priority-r-tree] Before answering a window-query by traversing the sub-branches, the prioritized R-tree first checks for overlap in its priority nodes.
[src:r-tree/priority-r-tree] The sub-branches are traversed (and constructed) by checking whether the least value of the first dimension of the query is above the value of the sub-branches.
[src:r-tree/priority-r-tree] This gives access to a quick indexation by the value of the first dimension of the bounding box.
[src:r-tree/priority-r-tree] Arge *et al.* writes that the priority tree always answers window-queries with $O\left(\left({\frac {N}{B}}\right)^{1-{\frac {1}{d}}}+{\frac {T}{B}}\right)$ I/Os, where N is the number of d-dimensional (hyper-) rectangles stored in the R-tree, B is the disk block size, and T is the output size.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] The key idea of the data structure is to group nearby objects and represent them with their minimum bounding rectangle in the next higher level of the tree; the "R" in R-tree is for rectangle.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Since all objects lie within this bounding rectangle, a query that does not intersect the bounding rectangle also cannot intersect any of the contained objects.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] At the leaf level, each rectangle describes a single object; at higher levels the aggregation includes an increasing number of objects.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] This can also be seen as an increasingly coarse approximation of the data set.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Similar to the B-tree, the R-tree is also a balanced search tree (so all leaf nodes are at the same depth), organizes the data in pages, and is designed for storage on disk (as used in databases).
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Each page can contain a maximum number of entries, often denoted as M .
[src:r-tree/r-tree] It also guarantees a minimum fill (except for the root node), however best performance has been experienced with a minimum fill of 30%–40% of the maximum number of entries (B-trees guarantee 50% page fill, and B*-trees even 66%).
[src:r-tree/r-tree] The reason for this is the more complex balancing required for spatial data as opposed to linear data stored in B-trees.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] As with most trees, the searching algorithms (e.g., intersection, containment, nearest neighbor search) are rather simple.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] The key idea is to use the bounding boxes to decide whether or not to search inside a subtree.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] In this way, most of the nodes in the tree are never read during a search.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Like B-trees, R-trees are suitable for large data sets and databases, where nodes can be paged to memory when needed, and the whole tree cannot be kept in main memory.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Even if data can be fit in memory (or cached), the R-trees in most practical applications will usually provide performance advantages over naive check of all objects when the number of objects is more than few hundred or so.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] However, for in-memory applications, there are similar alternatives that can provide slightly better performance or be simpler to implement in practice.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] To maintain in-memory computing for R-tree in a computer cluster where computing nodes are connected by a network, researchers have used RDMA (Remote Direct Memory Access) to implement data-intensive applications under R-tree in a distributed environment.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] This approach is scalable for increasingly large applications and achieves high throughput and low latency performance for R-tree.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] The key difficulty of R-tree is to build an efficient tree that on one hand is balanced (so the leaf nodes are at the same height) on the other hand the rectangles do not cover too much empty space and do not overlap too much (so that during search, fewer subtrees need to be processed).
[src:r-tree/r-tree] For example, the original idea for inserting elements to obtain an efficient tree is to always insert into the subtree that requires least enlargement of its bounding box.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Once that page is full, the data is split into two sets that should cover the minimal area each.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Most of the research and improvements for R-trees aims at improving the way the tree is built and can be grouped into two objectives: building an efficient tree from scratch (known as bulk-loading) and performing changes on an existing tree (insertion and deletion).
[src:r-tree/r-tree] R-trees do not guarantee good worst-case performance, but generally perform well with real-world data.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] The (bulk-loaded) Priority R-tree variant of the R-tree is worst-case optimal, but due to its increased complexity it has remained confined to theoretical study and has not received much attention in practical applications.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] When data is organized in an R-tree, the neighbors within a given distance r and the k nearest neighbors (for any Lp-Norm) of all points can efficiently be computed using a spatial join.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] This is beneficial for many algorithms based on such queries, for example the Local Outlier Factor.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] DeLi-Clu, Density-Link-Clustering is a cluster analysis algorithm that uses the R-tree structure for a similar kind of spatial join to efficiently compute an OPTICS clustering.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Data in R-trees is organized in pages that can have a variable number of entries (up to some pre-defined maximum, and usually above a minimum fill).
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Each entry within a non-leaf node stores two pieces of data: a way of identifying a child node, and the bounding box of all entries within this child node.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Leaf nodes store the data required for each child, often a point or bounding box representing the child and an external identifier for the child.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] For point data, the leaf entries can be just the points themselves.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] For polygon data (that often requires the storage of large polygons) the common setup is to store only the MBR (minimum bounding rectangle) of the polygon along with a unique identifier in the tree.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] The search process in an R-tree embodies a two-phase approach that aligns with the Filter and Refine Principle (FRP).
[src:r-tree/r-tree] In this structure, the internal nodes serve as an initial filter by quickly excluding regions of space that do not intersect the query, while the leaf nodes provide a refined, precise evaluation by storing the actual spatial objects.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Specifically, in range searching, the input is a search rectangle (Query box).
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Searching is quite similar to searching in a B+ tree.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] The search starts from the root node of the tree.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Every internal node contains a set of rectangles and pointers to the corresponding child node and every leaf node contains the rectangles of spatial objects (the pointer to some spatial object can be there).
[src:r-tree/r-tree] For every rectangle in a node, it has to be decided if it overlaps the search rectangle or not.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] If yes, the corresponding child node has to be searched also.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Searching is done like this in a recursive manner until all overlapping nodes have been traversed.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] When a leaf node is reached, the contained bounding boxes (rectangles) are tested against the search rectangle and their objects (if there are any) are put into the result set if they lie within the search rectangle.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] For priority search such as nearest neighbor search, the query consists of a point or rectangle.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] The root node is inserted into the priority queue.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Until the queue is empty or the desired number of results have been returned the search continues by processing the nearest entry in the queue.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Tree nodes are expanded and their children reinserted.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Leaf entries are returned when encountered in the queue.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] This approach can be used with various distance metrics, including great-circle distance for geographic data.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] To insert an object, the tree is traversed recursively from the root node.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] At each step, all rectangles in the current directory node are examined, and a candidate is chosen using a heuristic such as choosing the rectangle which requires least enlargement.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] The search then descends into this page, until reaching a leaf node.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] If the leaf node is full, it must be split before the insertion is made.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Again, since an exhaustive search is too expensive, a heuristic is employed to split the node into two.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Adding the newly created node to the previous level, this level can again overflow, and these overflows can propagate up to the root node; when this node also overflows, a new root node is created and the tree has increased in height.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] The algorithm needs to decide in which subtree to insert.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] When a data object is fully contained in a single rectangle, the choice is clear.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] When there are multiple options or rectangles in need of enlargement, the choice can have a significant impact on the performance of the tree.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] The objects are inserted into the subtree that needs the least enlargement.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] A Mixture heuristic is employed throughout.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] What happens next is it tries to minimize the overlap (in case of ties, prefer least enlargement and then least area); at the higher levels, it behaves similar to the R-tree, but on ties again preferring the subtree with smaller area.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] The decreased overlap of rectangles in the R*-tree is one of the key benefits over the traditional R-tree.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Since redistributing all objects of a node into two nodes has an exponential number of options, a heuristic needs to be employed to find the best split.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] In the classic R-tree, Guttman proposed two such heuristics, called QuadraticSplit and LinearSplit.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] In quadratic split, the algorithm searches for the pair of rectangles that is the worst combination to have in the same node, and puts them as initial objects into the two new groups.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] It then searches for the entry which has the strongest preference for one of the groups (in terms of area increase) and assigns the object to this group until all objects are assigned (satisfying the minimum fill).
[src:r-tree/r-tree] In addition to having a more advanced splitting heuristic, the R*-tree also tries to avoid splitting a node by reinserting some of the node members, which is similar to the way a B-tree balances overflowing nodes.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] This was shown to also reduce overlap and thus increase tree performance.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Finally, the X-tree can be seen as a R*-tree variant that can also decide to not split a node, but construct a so-called super-node containing all the extra entries, when it doesn't find a good split (in particular for high-dimensional data).
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Deleting an entry from a page may require updating the bounding rectangles of parent pages.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] However, when a page is underfull, it will not be balanced with its neighbors.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] Instead, the page will be dissolved and all its children (which may be subtrees, not only leaf objects) will be reinserted.
[src:r-tree/r-tree] If during this process the root node has a single element, the tree height can decrease.
